    <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-6">
    When to use this pattern
    </h2>
    <p>
    A-Z lists are great to categorise a large number of pages under one subject, but they only work when users know the name of the thing they're looking for, and that it sits under the specific subject. 
    </p>
    <p>
    We've found users preferring an A-Z list of pages over search. In testing we've seen users chose to use the A-Z because they were not sure they could spell a medical term such as 'appendicitis' to search for it, but expected to find it in the A-Z.
    </p>

    <p>
    NHS.UK currently uses A-Z on the following subjects:
    </p>
    
    <ul>
	<li><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/">Conditions</a></li> 
	<li><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/medicines/">Medicines</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>
    When not to use this pattern
    </h2>
    
    <p>Don't use the A-Z pattern:</p>

    <ul>
	<li>to group non-related subject pages</li>
	<li>as part of a transactional service</li>
  <li>as part of a content page</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Elements of the A-Z pattern</h2>

        <h3>
    A-Z navigation
    </h3>

            {{ designExample({
      type: 'a-z-nav'
    }) }}

    <p class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-4">
  Use the A-Z navigation at the top of the page.
   </p>




    <h3 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-6">
    A-Z list panel
    </h3>
        {{ designExample({
      type: 'a-z-list-panel'
    }) }}
   
   
    <p class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-4">
   Use the A-Z list panel below the A-Z navigation to allow users to navigate around a large section, for example a group of medicines. The example on this page is from the <a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/">Health A-Z</a> page on nhs.uk.
    </p>

    <p>
    The 'Back to top' link allows users to quickly jump back up the the A-Z navigation.
    </p>


  

    <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-8">
      Research on this pattern
    </h2>

    <p>
    During a research lab in 2018 using <a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/">Health A-Z</a>: All users were able to use the A-Z list, and this behaved as they expected.
    </p>

    <p>
    However, some users missed the quick anchor links at the top of the page, instead opting to scroll through all items. In these cases users found the list overwhelming.
    </p>

    <p>
    Some users did not use the “back to top” links, instead opting to scroll to the top of the page.
    </p>

    

